1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Bd3 O-O 6. Nge2 c5 7. d5 e6 8. Bg5 ({
Rather unusual. After} 8. O-O exd5 9. cxd5 {we would reach the tabyia of the
Penrose system, named after the British player who used it to defeat the
legendary Mikhail Tal. White's standard plan of development consists of h2,
Ng3, f4, Be3, Qf3. The bishop goes to g5 only in the event of certain black
setups (such as ...b6 followed by ...Ba6).}) 8... h6 9. Bf4 {Another
unexpected move. White intends to prevent the natural development of the enemy
queen's knight to d7. However, by blocking the f-pawn, he ensures temporary
stability to the other knight on e5.} ({Over the past years, Vladimir Georgiev
has constantly combined the Penrose setup with the retreat of the bishop to h4,
to which we would transpose after} 9. Bh4 exd5 10. cxd5 (10. exd5 {relieves
Black of the permanent threat of e4-e5 and is not likely to cause him dynamic
problems. Howeever, his position would become passive if he does not find a
way to fight for the initiative. here is such a possible way:} Nbd7 {[%csl Rd3]
[%cal Gd7e5]} 11. f4 g5 $5 12. fxg5 Ng4 13. Qd2 Nde5 14. Bh7+ Kh8 $1 $132 {
Thorbergsson,F-Penrose,J/Leipzig 1960/EXT 99 (0-1, 25).  It is interesting to
see Penrose on the black side!}) 10... Nbd7 $5 {Refraining from ...a6 makes
some sense from the tactical point of view.} (10... a6 11. a4 Nbd7 12. O-O Ne5
(12... Qc7 13. h3 Re8 14. f4 c4 15. Bc2 Nc5 16. Bxf6 $5 {This is Georgiev's
idea. This exchange is essential for the following pawn break.} Bxf6 17. e5
dxe5 18. f5 $44 {Georgiev,V (2567)-Valuet,B (2303)/Differdange 2007/CBM 119
ext (1-0, 38)}) 13. Bc2 $6 ({The critical line is} 13. f4 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Re8 15.
Ng3 {, similar to the position without ...a6 and a4.}) 13... g5 $1 14. Bg3 Nh5
{Black gets good play on the dark squares now.} 15. Bxe5 Bxe5 16. Ra3 Rb8 17.
Nc1 Nf4 18. Nd3 Nxd3 19. Bxd3 Qf6 20. Qc2 Qg6 21. Rb1 f5 {and Black had little
to complain about in Fominyh,A (2515)-Khomyakov,V (2340)/Moscow 1994/EXT 97 
(0-1, 40)}) 11. O-O Ne5 12. f4 Nxd3 13. Qxd3 Re8 14. Ng3 (14. Kh1 {is too slow,
allowing Black to start his queenside counterplay quite comfortably.} a6 15. a4
Rb8 16. Ng3 b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. Nxb5 Qb6 $44 {Georgiev,V (2596)-Piscopo,P 
(2321)/Reggio Emilia 2004/CBM 097 ext (1/2-1/2, 22)}) 14... b5 $5 {This would
not be possible so soon after ...a6 and a4.} 15. Bxf6 $5 {An attempt to
improve over an older game of his own.} (15. Qxb5 Bd7 16. Qa6 Qb6 17. Qxb6 axb6
{Georgiev,V (2538)-Smetankin,S (2485)/Chicago 2006 (0-1, 38)}) 15... Bxf6 16.
e5 $1 dxe5 17. f5 e4 {This is the only possible moment to open the long
diagonal, but it gives back the pawn without extinguishing White's initiative:}
(17... c4 18. Qe4 {[%cal Gf1f2,Ga1f1,Gf5g6]} g5 19. Nh5 $44) 18. Ncxe4 Bd4+ 19.
Kh1 $40 {Georgiev,V (2567)-Vandevoort,P (2364)/Charleroi 2007/CBM 119 ext (1-0,
26). Black still needs to find the optimal plan in this line.}) ({From the
historical point of view, the following blitz game is not without importance:} 
9. Bd2 $5 Nbd7 10. b3 {Who else would play that solid?} exd5 11. cxd5 a6 12.
O-O b5 13. f4 c4 14. bxc4 Nc5 15. Bc2 b4 16. e5 dxe5 17. fxe5 Ng4 $36 {
Petrosian,T-Fischer,R/Herceg Novi, blitz  1970/Fischer (0-1, 42)}) 9... Ng4 $5
$146 (9... exd5 10. cxd5 Re8 {looks entirely playable.} 11. Ng3 a6 12. a4 Qc7
13. O-O Nbd7 14. Qc1 Kh7 15. Re1 Rb8 16. Be2 h5 $6 {Black should not make the
g5-square available so soon.} (16... c4 $5 $132) 17. Bg5 c4 18. Qf4 {White has
considerably activated his play.} Kg8 19. Bh6 Bh8 20. h3 b5 21. axb5 axb5 22.
b4 $1 $14 {White has managed to block the queenside and enjoys a stable
advantage in the centre, Jussupow,A (2575)-Suetin,A (2460)/Moscow 1981/MCL 
(1-0, 90). Please note that this last move would have been less efficient with
the queen on c1, because of the simple ...cxb3, when Nxb5 can be answered by ..
.Qxc1 followed by ...b2.}) 10. Qd2 Na6 11. a3 $6 ({To passive. Eljanov might
have feared that} 11. Rd1 Nb4 12. Bb1 {would allow Black too much activity,
but there is no simple way to take advantage of it.}) 11... Nc7 12. f3 Ne5 {
Black wisely delayed the exchange on d5. In a "normal" Benoni, White could
simply retreat with the attacked bishop to c2, but here the c4-pawn is hanging.
} 13. O-O exd5 14. cxd5 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 {The first comment that comes to one's
mind is "Black has the pair of bishops". However, I believe that for a Benoni
it is more relevant that he has managed to exchange one pair of minor pieces 
(other than his g7-bishop!) which allows him to find comfortable squares for
the remaining pieces. This is quite a logical aim for Black, who has constant
problems with space.} b6 $1 {Completely in accordance with... Philidor's
recommendations. If you have a light-squared bishop, you should arrange your
pawns on dark squares, in order to prevent restricting the bishop's action and,
in fact, "complete" it. In our concrete case, the other bishop does not mind:
it has a wonderful diagonal at its disposal...} 16. Qd2 Kh7 17. Ng3 Ba6 {The
bishop stands nicely here, but the final result of this hyper-activity might
come as a slight surprise...} 18. Rfe1 Re8 19. a4 Bc4 20. Nf1 {After this move,
Black gets even more comfortable play. It was essential to question the
bishop's stability somehow.} ({However,} 20. Qc2 $6 {would be wrong because of
[%cal Gb2b3]} Na6 $1) (20. Ra3 $5 {might be better.[%cal Gb2b3]}) 20... Bxf1 $1
{Despite losing a tempo, this new exchange solves Black's spatial problems
completely! His pieces will soon be placed in a very harmonious way, enabling
favourable pawn moves on both wings. This does not mean that White is worse
already; his advantage in space and the compact centre insures him against
trouble in the near future. However, from a practical point of view, Black's
play is much easier to carry out, while White should restrict himself to
defensive measures.} 21. Rxf1 a6 22. Bg3 Qd7 23. Rae1 ({This is not a real
mistake yet, but it prepares a strategic blunder. With Black, I would be more
worried about} 23. Rab1 {, aiming to keep Black's queenside play under control,
for instance} b5 24. b4 (24. axb5 {would leave Black the choice between 24...
axb5, which opens the a-file for the rook and} Nxb5 {activating the knight.
Now,} 25. Nxb5 axb5 26. b4 {would be less effective because after} c4 $1 {the
c4-pawn would not be blocked.}) 24... cxb4 (24... c4 $6 {would allow White
block the position to his favour with} 25. a5 $1 {This last move is essential
in order to prevent ...bxa4 followed by ...Nb5. This is a typical 
(unfavourable) situation for the Benoni player. The knight that has been so
useful to help the queenside pawns get into motion, is placed very passively
now and could become the main cause for Black's troubles.}) 25. Rxb4 {. White
plans to increase his pressure with Rfb1, while after} a5 {he has the thematic
exchange sacrifice} 26. Rxb5 {at his disposal, when the permanent weakness of
the d6-pawn would offer him reasonable compensation.}) 23... b5 24. f4 $2 ({
The position lost its initial character of a Penrose Attack a long time ago.
The last move only creates weaknesses, without creating real chances for an
attack. It would have been better to restrict Black's initiative with, say,} 
24. b3) 24... b4 25. Nd1 f5 $1 ({The point. The g3-bishop is reduced to
passivity now, while the d5-pawn becomes chronically weak. Eljanov probably
counted on} 25... Qxa4 $6 26. f5 {with an attack.}) 26. exf5 Qxf5 27. Ne3 Rxe3
$1 {Further simplification...} 28. Rxe3 Bd4 29. Bf2 Bxe3 30. Bxe3 {The bishop
has changed diagonals, but is far from reaching any form of activity.} Nxd5 31.
Rd1 Re8 (31... Nxe3 32. Qxe3 Qf6 {was an important alternative. Radjabov
probably feared that the vulnerability of his king would make itself felt in
the presence of queens and preferred not to give up his centralisation so
easily.}) 32. Bf2 $2 ({The losing move. Why preserve such an awfully passive
piece from exchange? It is true that the endgame arising after} 32. Qxd5 Qxd5
33. Rxd5 Rxe3 34. Rxd6 Rb3 35. Rd2 c4 {looks promising for Black, in view of
his huge advantage in space on the queenside and his active rook, but White
would have been alive.}) 32... Nxf4 33. Qxd6 $2 Qe4 {Suddenly, there is no
reasonable defence against the threat of mate in one. The bishop is really a
bad piece, preventing the defence along the second rank.} 0-1

