1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6 5. b3 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Be7 7. Bg2 c6 8. O-O
d5 9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. Rd1 O-O 11. a4 {This position is the starting point of my
recent opening database included with CBM 121.} c5 12. Na3 Bb7 13. Qb2 Rc8 14.
Rac1 Ne4 15. Be1 Bf6 16. b4 Ba8 {This was recommended by Jussupow as leading
to equality, but I believe that White's superior mobilization offers him
realistic chances for an advantage.} (16... cxd4 {Jussupow,A (2620)-Kharitonov,
A (2550)/Moscow 1988/URS-ch/[ChessBase] (1-0, 59)}) 17. e3 {White strengthens
his control over the central d4-square, but somewhat weakens the light squares.
} ({In my article I recommended} 17. Qb1 {with the possible continuation} Qe7
18. cxd5 Bxd5 (18... exd5 19. Nb5 a6 20. Nc3 $14) 19. dxc5 bxc5 20. Nc4 {[%csl
Gc4][%cal Gb4b5]} cxb4 21. Bxb4 Ndc5 22. Nfe5 $14 (22. Nfd2 $6 Nxf2 $1 23. Kxf2
Rb8 $44) 22... Nxf2 $2 23. Kxf2 Rb8 24. Bxd5 Rxb4 25. Nc6 $16 {Only further
practice will prove if there is anything wrong in these lines.}) 17... cxd4 18.
exd4 dxc4 {At first sight, this looks like a complete strategic success for
Black. In Isolani structures, the white light-squared bishop is not well
placed on g2, because it can be exchanged, leaving the d5-square chronically
weak.} 19. Ne5 $1 {After this move, Kramnik's idea becomes obvious. With ...
Ne4 and ...Bf6 Black has weakened the control over the critical d5-square and
placed two of his pieces on vulnerable squares. White aims for dynamic play in
what is basically a static structure.} Bg5 $1 {The correct reaction!  Black
provokes the move f4, in order to get the possibility of consolidating his
knight on e4.} ({The "natural developing move"} 19... Qe7 $6 {allows White get
a dominating position with} 20. Qe2 Nd6 21. Bxa8 Rxa8 22. Nc6 Qe8 23. b5 $16 {
[%csl Gc6][%cal Ga3c4]}) (19... Bd5 20. Naxc4 $14 {leaves Black slightly
hanging, too.[%cal Gc4e3]}) ({The immediate} 19... Be7 {is less adequate,
because after} 20. Naxc4 $14 {the move played in the game} f5 $6 {hardly makes
sense.}) 20. f4 (20. Ra1 $2 c3 $17) (20. Rxc4 $2 Nxe5 21. Rxc8 Nf3+ 22. Bxf3
Qxc8 $15) 20... Be7 21. Naxc4 {White has to eliminate this pawn before
anything.} (21. d5 $6 Nxe5 (21... Bxd5 $2 22. Bxe4 $18) (21... exd5 $2 22. Bxe4
$16) (21... c3 $5) 22. fxe5 c3 $1 {spoils White's coordination.}) 21... f5 ({
But now, the threat d5 was real:} 21... f6 $6 22. d5 $1 $16) 22. Ne3 {Both
sides have taken the important squares under control, but White remains
slightly better developed. On the other hand, Black's structure is more
compact.} Rxc1 23. Qxc1 $1 (23. Rxc1 Nxe5 24. dxe5 Qd3 $15) 23... Ndf6 (23...
Nxe5 $6 24. dxe5 $36 {would allow White to occupy the seventh rank with one of
his pieces.}) 24. Nc6 Qc7 25. b5 {White has expanded his area of dimination,
but Black will do just the same.} Nd5 (25... Bxc6 $6 {is probably premature:}
26. Qxc6 Qxc6 27. bxc6 Rc8 28. Rc1 Nd5 29. Nxd5 exd5 30. Bh3 g6 31. g4 $36) 26.
Nxd5 exd5 {[%cal Gf8c8]} 27. Nxe7+ Qxe7 $11 {The position has calmed down.
White's advantage in space on the queenside and his pair of bishops offer him
some remote hope of a better ending. However, Gelfand will prove that his
stability on the light squares is just enough to maintain the balance even.}
28. Qb2 Rc8 29. Rc1 Rc4 30. Bf1 Nd6 $1 {An exchange sacrifice in the spirit of
the 11th game of the Wch match Petrosian-Spassky 1969.} 31. Qa3 (31. Bxc4 $2
dxc4 $40 {[%csl Gg1][%cal Ge7e4,Ge7b7]}) 31... Qe4 32. Bf2 Rxc1 33. Qxc1 Nc4
34. Qd1 Bb7 35. Bd3 Qe6 36. Qh5 Nd6 37. Qe2 Qxe2 38. Bxe2 Kf7 39. Be1 Bc8 40.
Kf2 Nc4 41. Bb4 g6 42. Ke1 a6 {Eliminating the last source of worries.} 43.
bxa6 Bxa6 44. Bc3 Bb7 45. Kf2 Bc6 46. Bd1 Nd6 47. Ke3 Ke6 48. Bb3 1/2-1/2

