1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Nf3 e5 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Be3
Re8 $5 {A relatively rare move. Black provokes his opponent into locking the
centre, but theory considers that the rook will remain misplaced after:} 9. d5
{, when Black's counterplay is based on ...f5.} Nh5 10. g3 Bf8 {A couple of
years ago, a very good friend of mine mentioned this plan to me. In the King's
Indian, Black frequently suffers from lack of space for his minor pieces.
After the bishop's retreat, such a regrouping is enabled: ...Nh5-g7, ...Be7, ..
.f5, ...Rf8 and ...Nf6. My friend also added that White can spare several
tempi (four, if I counted well, although this is slightly exaggerated: With
the bishop on g7, White has to spend a tempo with g3, weakening his kingside
